Lord willing we will all remain healthy and determined and free in all the important ways.

This week we are sharing about the power of affirmations. 

Affirmations are like high octane intention for me and living intentionally is what keeps me in balance. We all deal with our lives differently and I love to steer clear of the corny and sanctimonious, but mental hygiene is like style and beauty advice: I’m going to share mine and if it doesn’t work for you, there are  18 bagillion women to watch on here so scroll on!

I do feel that it’s important to normalize fluxes in emotion while finding ways to work with ourselves. Maybe it comes from working with so many millennials and genz folk, but it’s okay to shed the toxic stiff upper lip of our generation, feel the feels and move on through.

When I was in first grade I vividly remember wanting the long, straight hair of the girl who sat in front of me. I was always teased for my hair…all kinds of names. I didn’t know anyone else with very curly hair (until my baby sister was born!) besides my aunt who straightened hers and was always wrapping mine to get it straight. 
As an adult I spent decades in a pixie or wearing it up all the time.
Hated it was an understatement.
Definitely a First World problem, but tell that to a little girl with a fierce personality and wild hair to go with it,  in a world where standing out was not a good thing.

This month as a #lusbrandspartner we are sharing our curly journeys. 
At 55, finding the right products has helped me to like my hair more than I thought I could. But I am still amazed at the DMs asking for my products and routine!! 😅

This week on Fridays with the Fab4 we are sharing our love of travel.

I don’t think most people need to be told to travel and I’m sure very many people reading this have traveled to many wonderful places. So I am making this one more personal. I don’t just want to travel, I need to travel. I mean anywhere. The next state will do. For many years my profession required it.
For several years (raising kids) it was mostly domestic. It doesn’t matter. 
I get too busy.
I get too rigid.
I fight demons.

Fun fact about the first two shots:
We had very little time to get ready for the @uncommonthreadsboutique Gala on Thursday evening after an afternoon of touring the space and shopping at @uncommonthreads_closet 
I had intended to wear this beautiful @evafrancodesign confection to the party and wanted it to be photographed since we have some amazing photographers in this group.

Did I mention we were running late? That didn’t stop my girls from creating a little set for me, in perfect lighting in Diane’s home where she generously hosted all of us.
While I was in the other room changing I could hear them all rearranging things and talking about where I should stand for the perfect light. For me friendship is found in the things that may seem so small, or even silly to others. Acts of generosity unawares. They didn’t know it, but when I went back to the room to change into the other outfit, I ruined my mascara a little thinking about the sweet moment where I was put first and they thought nothing of it.

I am okay. I’ve got my girls.

This post is a little different. I will consider it a “get to know me” because if you knew me you would know that as much as I love to share and teach about being fabulous and empowered in midlife, what I care about most is my children.
Some may know already some of the facts of my life: I am 56, I am a retired opera singer and presently I teach others sing, I have two boys and my niece and nephew who were raised with them and they are why I work everyday to be the best I can be. Lisatandthecity is a love note to them and place for them to look back on me. Because the sad thing is that yesterday we crossed through another anniversary of the passing of my niece and nephew’s mom. We don’t have enough pictures of her and we don’t have enough recordings of the sound of her voice. She didn’t get a midlife. 
Now, as I approach an empty nest, I reflect on our life and how lucky I am to grow older with these magical people around me. Full of talent and humor and intelligence and sensitivity to the world around them. 
Michael is our baby and the name sake of his aunt. Last night in what was his last performance of his high school career at Fiorello H LaGuardia High School of Performing Arts he sang a song (written my friend and Tony Award Winning composer Jason Robert Brown) called “Flying Home” .
Michael could not have known when he auditioned for Rising Stars 2023 that the performance dates would land on the birth and death dates of the aunt whom he never met, but who has shaped his life in many ways. The lyrics were so poignant for these days,”There will be no worries, there will be no pain, I am on my way…I’ll be flying home”
I’m heading gratefully toward the empty nest because of all that it represents; the gift of moving on here in this beautiful and bountiful world full of hope in art and music and our young people.
Happy Weekend to you, friends.
OXL

✈️ Currently landing in Athens Greece! We have taken the 3 boys on a European Adventure. There is a lot to celebrate with two graduations and an empty-ish nest. Richie and Michael both stayed in NYC for college but don’t live at home. 
Rich and I know that even though we stay close there is a shift.

I must say I have always been a “use the oxygen mask first” and then put it on my kids kind of mom. I hope my niece, who is soon getting married and will start a family of her own, does the same. The world needs more women undaunted by empty nests because we never cast ourselves aside. Education, career, travel, hobbies, friendships and of course, self care; all paramount to our survival and therefore the best interests of the next generation. 

So here I am, out to drinks with my best friend last week at the top of the Mandarin Hotel in NYC. It’s just so fun to get dressed and enjoy our lives. 

Stay tuned in stories for our adventures here and in stories. Be sure to share yours too! We inspire one another when we intend to live every day.

“Bouche Mordue” refers to the blurred lipstick look worn ubiquitously by French Women. (Literally translated means Bitten Mouth)
💋
Not only is a fabulously chic makeup move, but it is a great way for women to dip their toe into the controversial waters of bold lips at a certain age.😯 
Color is our friend, Ladies, and nothing reminds us of how awesome we are like a bold (ish) lip.

Tips:
💋Keep the rest of your makeup simple, clean and slightly dewy
💄Choose a matte or Demi matte texture so that lipstick stays put and doesn’t leak into fine lines.
💋Use a concealer, primer or light powder around the lip edges to grip product and create a clean canvas.
💄Be confident with trying bold lip colors like reds, berries and bold pinks. There are choices for everyone. It’s a really fun approach to less is more makeup.

I don’t fully agree with the perspective that the Fashion and Beauty Industry is predicated on the idea that women have low self esteem and that it’s a patriarchal machine. 
First of all, the history of cosmetics needs to be considered.
AND, I have news for everyone: you don’t have to buy or do anything that doesn’t align with who you are or want to be…but I digress.
I for one, love to see the best version of myself looking back at me. I love to declare my evolution and create a new version of me every single day. 
I love to feel better when I feel like hell, with the flick of a red lipstick.
I love to say I’M STILL HERE BABY with a metallic jacket.

~Draw inspiration from others but never aim to imitate. It always lacks authenticity.
~Do not overbuy. It will rob you of creativity.
~Do not judge. If your style is a version of you, then so is someone else’s intimately tied to what’s going on with them. Let’s enjoy our differences.
~Donate. Share the versions of the you of the past with someone who will value it or in many cases, needs it.
~Choose carefully…make sure you are really dressing for YOU not someone else or a societal statement on age or appropriateness that feels inauthentic to you!

Do you need help with serums for a great morning routine?
I did. So I asked my dermatologist about the quickest morning line up for my midlife face. 
Oh and younger ladies…she to start most of these by age 28😘
You’re welcome.

There are obviously many products and tips out there but here are the basic facts:

** Vitamin C is key for brightening the skin and addresses hyperpigmentation and enhances collagen production. 
Ask your dermatologist what percentage is right for you.

**Hyaluronic Acid is a powerful humectant that can hold up to 1,000 times its weight in water, meaning it has an unbelievable ability to retain water and is why it’s a key ingredient in skincare products meant for parched complexions. Not only does this key anti-aging ingredient allow your skin to get the hydration it craves, but regular use of it can lead to the appearance of healthier, plumper, more dewy skin 

**Niacinimide, also known as vitamin B3  is a water-soluble vitamin that works with the natural substances in your skin to help visibly minimize enlarged pores, tighten lax or stretched out pores, improve uneven skin tone, soften fine lines and wrinkles, diminish dullness, and strengthen a weakened surface.
(Essential for midlife skin!)
It also reverses environmental damage.

Now, Obviously we need moisturizer but what’s right for you? Moisturizers work in one of two main ways: they either trap moisture in your skin to keep it from escaping, or they restore moisture in the outer layer of skin that’s already been lost.
Ask your dermatologist what’s right for your skin and remember that the key ingredients for your skin care goals are all you need.

My Top Three Makeup Tips that have nothing to do with the Makeup. Number Three may
Surprise you!!

Number 1: For smooth application every time be sure your skin is flake free. That includes your lips. Great makeup application requires a smooth canvas.
I love gentle manual exfoliators like this one from @boombycindyjoseph 
and the lip exfoliator from @freshbeauty . 
Sugar is with a little water makes a great exfoliation paste for lips as well!!

Number 2: Have a variety of quality brushes. They don’t have to break the bank, but they have a huge impact on the smooth and natural application on skin of any age-especially mature skin.
If you don’t want a whole set, Irecommend the following:
Powder
Foundation
Blush
and both precision and fluffy shadow brushes

Number 3: Don’t apply your makeup only from a straight on position. You would never just style the front of your hair, so don’t treat your makeup application as though you are one dimensional.

Consider all the angles that a makeup artist would during a
professional application.

Spots to consider for placement and blending:
~Side views of the high points of the face and outer corners of the eyes.
~Eyes lowered and straight on.
~Side view of the jawline and neck (Calling all my mature ladies!!!)

Afraid to wear red? Not sure which hue is right for you? 
Well, red is a classic which is currently trending as strong as the message it sends. Here are some tips to help you wear it, instead of it wearing you⬇️

~If you have a warm skin tone, you’ll look great in organic, warm colors like red, coral, and amber. 
~If you have a cool skin tone, reach for shades of red that are closer to maroon or rose. 
~If your skin has a neutral undertone, avoid reds with orange undertones and choose bluer shades or a bright, true red instead.
~If you are very fair, burgundy and deep crimson are your friends!
~If you have dark skin you can indulge in many fabulous shades: Try oxblood, crimson red, fiery red orange, Reds with strong pink undertones, auburn and especially Ruby Red.

Singing is one way that I express that.

When I was little, I wrote novels in my room, wrote music at my piano, directed other kids in singing and made them all put on productions that I directed, made the whole neighborhood play school and I was the teacher, put all my friends and my sisters in my mother’s gowns and organized weddings where I was the Priest, not the bride.
So I figured out that I’m not anyone’s mob wife…Since I was a little kid, I’ve been a creator and a BOSS.
Why wouldn’t I be? Look at how my people let me hold court in a fur coat and muff when I was two?
So I can’t lose my way in this middle chapter. I need to look at her every day and know that I’m her with deep forehead wrinkles and two necks😅
Even better. I earned her wisdom now.

**Pictured here my beautiful grandfather and my beloved Aunt (mother’s sister) who at the time was 20 years old. Her name was Paula Capone and she died at the Age of 52 due to complications of MS. She could walk until she was 34 and then she spent the rest of her years unable to use her body. She was cared for at home by my BAD A$$ grandmother who taught us all what love is.
She was my first style icon and she bought me the outfit I’m wearing here. This page is a love letter to her and my mother. She is the reason I move my body EVERYDAY-not because I have to but because I CAN. When I run, I whisper to her and ask her if she wants to get on my back.

So there it is. You know the thing that is most important to know about me.
Wishing you a Sunday full of wonder and deep gratitude.
